Equating as measurement error model

Chris Haid

April 22, 2014

So lets try test equating as a measurement error model and lets get some comparisons with Stan and JAGS. Lets assume that a student \(i \in N\) has an underlying ability measured on NWEAs RIT scale \(r_i>0 \forall i \in N\). The MAP provides a noisy measure of \(r\) that Ill denote \(\hat{r}\), where \(r = [r_{1}, r_{2}, \ldots, r_{N}]\) and similarly for \(\hat{r}\).

Well first sample the \(r_i\) from some likely scores and then create a noisy measure of each. Finally well linearly relate the \(r_i\) to anther noisy measure \(\hat{a} \in [0,1]\).

So first lets sample \(r\) from a known distribution

set.seed(432104)
require(rstan)
## Loading required package: rstan
## Loading required package: Rcpp
## Loading required package: inline

## Attaching package: 'inline'

## rstan (Version 2.6.0, packaged: 2015-02-06 21:02:34 UTC, GitRev: 198082f07a60)
N <- 30 # number of students

r<-rnorm(n = N, mean = 211.39, sd =5.83) #8th grade Math NWEA Norm
head(r)
## [1] 210.4599 224.6591 201.0468 215.6603 203.3875 229.2026

Now \(\hat{r}\) is noisily measured from \(r\):

sigma.r<-1.2
rhat<-rnorm(n=N, mean=r, sd=sigma.r)

head(rhat)
## [1] 209.5887 225.4890 201.5357 216.4288 204.1839 231.7385

And finally we simulate \(\hat{a}\) from \(r\) as well. In this case I want \(a\) to be on the on the \([0,1]\) scale and so I pick \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\) to normalize the \(r\)s on to that scale linearly:

  alpha <- -min(r)/diff(range(r))
  beta <- 1/diff(range(r))

  alpha
## [1] -5.411656
  beta
## [1] 0.02796169
  sigma.a=.01
  ahat <- rnorm(n = N, mean = alpha + beta*r, sd = sigma.a)
  ahat[ahat > 1] <- 1
  ahat[ahat < 0] <- 0

head(ahat)
## [1] 0.4819412 0.8738586 0.2192464 0.6110404 0.2525802 1.0000000

So we our data are the observed \(\hat{r}_i\)s and \(\hat{a}_i\)s. Our parameters of interest are the \(r\), \(\alpha\), and \(\beta\). I take the standard deviations\(\sigma_{r}\) and \(\sigma_a\) to be unknown hyper parameters. So heres a Stan model that should estimate these values:

model.1<-'
  data { 
    int<lower=0> N;
    real<lower=0,upper=1> ahat[N];
    real<lower=190, upper=240> rhat[N];
  }
  parameters{
    real alpha;
    real beta;
    real<lower=190, upper=240> r[N];
    real<lower=0> sigma_r;
    real<lower=0> sigma_a;
  }
  model{
    rhat ~ normal(r, sigma_r);
    for (i in 1:N) {
      ahat[i] ~ normal(alpha + beta * r[i], sigma_a) T[0,1];
    }
    alpha ~ normal(0,10);
    beta ~ normal(0,10);
    sigma_r ~ cauchy(0,5);
    sigma_a ~ cauchy(0,5);
  }
'

And now for the sampling:

stan.data <- list('ahat' = ahat,
                  'rhat' = rhat,
                  'N' = N)

fit1 <- stan(model_code = model.1,
                   data = stan.data,
                   #pars = c('a','r', 'alpha', 'beta'),
                   chains=2,
                   iter=100)
